===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
[[File:Huang character etymology Chi 2010 theory.svg|thumb|right|150px|HJ 32300, HJ 15675]]
{{zh-ref|Chi (2010)}} proposes that {{lang|zh|黃}} was originally a {{liushu|p|nocap=1}} and the original character of {{och-l|尪|a disabled person with a protruding chest or abdomen}}. It has been phonetically borrowed for "yellow" since the era of the oracle bone script. {{zh-ref|He (1998)}} noted the possible ritual of burning disabled people with a protruding chest or abdomen to pray for rain as mentioned in ''{{w|Zuozhuan|Zuozhuan}}''. The {{zh-l|*口}} in the upper part of the bronze inscription of {{lang|zh|黃}} might be depicting the disabled person's face facing upwards. Compare [[堇]].

{{zh-ref|Li (2012)}}, on the other hand, proposes that {{lang|zh|黃}} was originally a {{liushu|p|nocap=1}} and the original character of {{och-l|璜|semicircular jade}} as the {{zh-l|*口}} in the oracle bone script resembles a ring of jade, so the character would carry the meaning of "a man wearing a ring of jade on his chest". The meaning "yellow" is the result of [[rebus]]. See also the original version of [[周]], which represents carved jade.

According to ''{{w|Shuowen|Shuowen}}'', it is both a {{Han compound|炗|田|ls=psc|ls2=ic|c1=p|c2=s|t1=light|t2=field|nocap=1}} – the color of earth, with {{zh-l|*炗}} being the ancient form of {{och-l|光|light}}. However, this interpretation is erroneous as {{zh-l|*廿}} at the top was formed as a result of corruption of {{zh-l|*口}} in the bronze inscription.

===Etymology===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*hwaŋ||shine; bright; yellow}}. Cognate with {{och-l|光|light; bright}}, {{och-l|曠|bright; well-lit}}, {{cog|my|ဝင်း||bright}}, {{cog|my|ဝါ||yellow}}.
;“sexually obscene; pornographic”
